Most of the specimens known so far for
P. minuta
come from the Amazon rainforests of the Brazilian states of Rondônia and Amazonas . The transitional areas between these forests and the Brazilian savanna (Cerrado) are extremely fire-sensitive, and anthropogenic activities related with deforestation for crop and livestock establishment as well as global warming have shown negative effects on their biodiversity (Pivello 2009;
Shlisky et al. 2009
;
Silveira et al. 2013
).
